  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation folds an equality
comparison between two GEPs with the same base and one differing index: (gep %ptr,
%idx1) == (gep %ptr, %idx2) into (%idx1 == %idx2). This is only valid if pointer
arithmetic from indices to resulting addresses is injective (no wrap). In the
provided reproducer, the pointer size is 8 bits and the element size is 4 bytes.
Because indices are i8, %idx2 = 64 produces an effective offset of 256, which wraps
to 0 in the 8-bit pointer space; thus the two GEPs yield equal pointers while the
indices are unequal. InstCombine incorrectly assumes equality of indices implies
pointer equality regardless of potential wrap-around.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe
first (and only) transformation replaces the original icmp eq on pointers with icmp
eq on the i8 indices. No other analyses (AA etc.) contribute. The failing Alive2
check shows a concrete counterexample (idx1=0, idx2=64) where the original returns
true and the transformed returns false. This implicates foldGEPICmp's path for
NumDifferences == 1 guarded by CanFold(NW). CanFold currently returns true for
equality regardless of GEP nowrap flags, allowing the unsound fold.\n\n3. Root Cause
Analysis:\nIn foldGEPICmp, the lambda CanFold unconditionally returns true for
equality predicates:\n  auto CanFold = [Cond](GEPNoWrapFlags NW) { if
(ICmpInst::isEquality(Cond)) return true; ... }\nThis permits folding even when
neither GEP has nowrap flags (NW == none), so potential unsigned pointer wrap is
ignored. Equality of pointer results after wrapping is not equivalent to equality of
indices. Similar unsoundness applies to other equality folds in this function that
rely on CanFold (e.g., (gep Ptr, OFFSET) cmp Ptr -> (OFFSET cmp 0) and (gep Ptr,
OFFSET1) cmp (gep Ptr, OFFSET2) -> (OFFSET1 cmp OFFSET2)). The code comments earlier
(lines 658-663 in transformToIndexedCompare) explicitly rely on only inbounds GEPs to
guarantee no overflow for a similar rewrite; foldGEPICmp lacks such a guard for
equality.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Points(s):\nEdit lines 691-698 in
llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCompares.cpp to change CanFold so that
equality comparisons are only folded when we have a guarantee of no unsigned wrap
(i.e., NW.hasNoUnsignedWrap()). This ensures pointer arithmetic remains injective
with respect to indices. Revised lambda:\n  auto CanFold = [Cond](GEPNoWrapFlags NW)
{\n    if (ICmpInst::isEquality(Cond))\n      // For equality, only fold when pointer
addition cannot wrap. Without\n      // no-unsigned-wrap, distinct indices may
produce equal wrapped pointers.\n      return NW.hasNoUnsignedWrap();\n
assert(ICmpInst::isUnsigned(Cond));\n    return NW != GEPNoWrapFlags::none();\n
};\nThis change prevents the unsound fold in the reproducer (both GEPs have NW ==
none) while preserving existing optimizations when nowrap information is available
(e.g., inbounds GEPs).\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy tightening the folding condition to
require no-unsigned-wrap for equality predicates, we eliminate the incorrect
transformation that ignores address space wrap-around. The reproducer will no longer
be transformed; Alive2 will confirm equivalence. Optimizations on safe cases (with
nowrap flags) remain unaffected.\n",
